06786nam a22009015i 9781845458546DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454585467 a10.1515/97818454585462doi  a(DE-B1597)636014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a302.2322200aTheorising Media and Practice /ced. by Birgit Bräuchler, John Postill. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnthropology of Media ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Theorising Media and Practice -- tPART 1 Media as Practice -- tCHAPTER 1 Theorising Media as Practice -- tCHAPTER 2 What Do We Mean by ‘Media Practices’? -- tCHAPTER 3 Media as Practice: A Brief Exchange -- tPART II Media, Culture and Practice -- tCHAPTER 4 From Fan Practice to Mediated Moments: The Value of Practice Theory in the Understanding of Media Audiences -- tCHAPTER 5 Thick Context, Deep Epistemology: A Meditation on Wide-Angle Lenses on Media, Knowledge Production and the Concept of Culture -- tCHAPTER 6 ‘But It Is My Habit to Read the Times’: Metaculture and Practice in the Reading of Indian Newspapers -- tCHAPTER 7 Embedded/Embedding Media Practices and Cultural Production -- tPART III Media Practices in Context -- tChapter 8 Communication, Cognition and Usage: Epistemological Considerations of Media Practices and Processes -- tCHAPTER 9 Language-games, In/dividuals and Media Uses: What a Practice Perspective Should Imply for Media Studies -- tCHAPTER 10 A Barthian Approach to Practice and Media: Internet Engagements among Teleworkers in Rural Denmark -- tCHAPTER 11 Can Practice Theory Inspire Studies of ICTs in Everyday Life? -- tPART IV New Media Production Practices -- tCHAPTER 12 Playful Practices: Theorising ‘New Media’ Cultural Production -- tCHAPTER 13 Theorising the Practices of Free Software: The Movement -- tCHAPTER 14 Cinematography and Camera Crew: Practice, Process and Procedure -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough practice theory has been a mainstay of social theory for nearly three decades, so far it has had very limited impact on media studies. This book draws on the work of practice theorists such as Wittgenstein, Foucault, Bourdieu, Barth and Schatzki and rethinks the study of media from the perspective of practice theory. Drawing on ethnographic case studies from places such as Zambia, India, Hong Kong, the United States, Britain, Norway and Denmark, the contributors address a number of important themes: media as practice; the interlinkage between media, culture and practice; the contextual study of media practices; and new practices of digital production. Collectively, these chapters make a strong case for the importance of theorising the relationship between media and practice and thereby adding practice theory as a new strand to the study of anthropology of media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMass media and anthropologyvCongresses. 0aMass media and culturevCongresses. 0aMass mediaxResearchvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAlsina, Pau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArdèvol, Elisenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBird, S. Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBräuchler, Birgit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristensen, Toke H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelio, Gemma San, econtributor.